issue_body:
Mustache template application can be (relatively) expensive, especially in the case of ingest processor execution where we necessarily have to perform it on every document.

There's an edge case of the `date` ingest processor where template application is applied in a loop. Consider the following:

```
PUT _ingest/pipeline/date
{
  "processors": [
    {
      "date": {
        "timezone": "{{{ timezone }}}",
        "field": "date",
        "formats": [
          [...]
        ]
      }
    }
  ]
}

POST _ingest/pipeline/date/_simulate
{
  "docs": [
    {
      "_index": "index",
      "_id": "id",
      "_source": {
        "date": "funtimesahead",
        "timezone": "UTC"
      }
    }
  ]
}
```

In this case, for each document that's processed by the pipeline, we'd attempt to parse `"funtimesahead"` with each format in order until the value is successfully parsed -- that's fine (so to speak). What's not fine is that we happen to run mustache template evaluation inside that loop! The timezone is always going to be `"UTC"` and we can apply the template just once before the loop in order to determine that.

The same issue applies for locale.

-----

Separately (and I doubt there's much we can do about this without eating a breaking change, though perhaps we should document it) -- using a templated value for timezone and locale is not cooperative when the values might not be present. (edit: TODO I need to write this up better, this might warrant being its own separate bug, but I needed somewhere to put the note for now so it's not lost to time.)

The `index.mode` setting is an index setting that is somewhat special. Besides that it validates itself, it also validation other index settings. Unfortunately this doesn't always kick in. 

When creating a new index it does kick in:

```
PUT index1
{
  "settings": {
    "index.time_series.start_time": "2000-01-01T00:00Z",
    "index.time_series.end_time": "2000-01-01T00:00Z"
  }
}
```

However when creating a new index and then updating the index settings the `index.mode` validation does not kick in:

```
PUT index1

PUT /_settings
{
  "settings": {
    "index.time_series.end_time": "2000-01-02T00:00Z"
  }
}

GET index1
```

This leaves the cluster in a bad state, as the validation does kick in later during unrelated operations. Like updating another unrelated index setting or when a new node joins the cluster.

Note that if `index.mode` index setting is configured to `standard`, then the index mode validation does kick in

The expect outcome is that when updating index settings that `index.mode` validation is also performed.

